### TIER 4: APPRENTICESHIP PROGRAMS (Paid On-the-Job Training)

#### **Apprenticeship D.1 — Oregon Registered Apprenticeships (Electrical, Plumbing, HVAC, Machinist)**

**Program Type:** Registered Apprenticeships (federal + state recognized)  
**Available Through:** Clackamas Community College, Rogue Community College, Lane Community College  
**Cost to Apprentice:** FREE or low-cost (PAID on-the-job training)  
**Earning While Training:** $18–$28/hour starting; increases with skill progression  

**Apprenticeship Options:**

**Electrical Trades (4–5 years)**
- Inside Electrical (high voltage) — 4–5 years
- Limited Energy (low voltage) — 2–3 years
- Limited Maintenance Electrician — 2 years

**Plumbing (4 years)**
- Full apprenticeship pathway
- Journeyperson license

**HVAC (varies)**
- Heating, ventilation, air conditioning
- Growing field; strong job security

**Machinist (3 years)**
- Industrial machinery repair
- Technical + precision work

**Painting (3 years)**
- Construction trade

**Why Apprenticeships Are Valuable:**
- **You earn while you learn** (unlike bootcamps)
- Paid on-the-job training; wages start immediately
- Journeyperson license upon completion (nationally recognized)
- Union apprenticeships (benefits, job security, pension)
- **Wage progression:** $18–$20/hr start → $50–$70/hr journeyperson
- High barrier to recidivism: Good income, union support, strong community

**Reentry-Specific Advantages:**
- WIOA funding for justice-involved individuals
- Many local unions actively recruit returning citizens
- Apprenticeship.gov has dedicated REO programs
- Physical trade allows for "fresh start" mindset

**Application Process:**
1. Research trade via oregonapprenticeship.org
2. Locate JATC (Joint Apprenticeship Training Committee) for trade
3. Apply directly to JATC (not colleges)
4. Complete application + JATC interview
5. If accepted: Enter "applicant pool"
6. When sponsors have openings: JATC contacts you
7. Once employed: Attend CCC/Rogue/Lane (concurrent with paid work)
8. Progress 2–5 years depending on trade
9. Final exams → Journeyperson license

**Timeline:**
- Application → JATC interview: 1–3 months
- Applicant pool wait: 3–12 months
- Once working: 2–5 year apprenticeship
- Total: 3–7 years to full journeyperson credential

**Earnings During Training:**
- Year 1: ~$18–$22/hour
- Year 2: ~$22–$28/hour
- Year 3: ~$28–$35/hour
- Year 4–5: ~$40–$60/hour
- **Post-journeyperson:** $55–$80/hour (union scale)

**Why This Matters:** Trade work is recession-resistant, provides identity + community, clear wage progression. "Fresh start" is psychologically powerful.

**Priority Index:** 8.2/10

